** Deep Neural Networks increase representational power by stacking multiple nonlinear layers **
As depth increases, the network applies repeated linear transformations followed by nonlinear activations.
Unlike shallow models, deeper networks can capture complex nonlinear patterns.
The core computation remains weighted sum + bias, but applied multiple times hierarchically.

** Learning Mechanism **

The model learns using forward propagation and backpropagation.
Mean Squared Error (MSE) is used to measure prediction error.
Gradients are computed using the chain rule across all layers.
Weights and biases are updated using gradient descent.
Greater depth allows richer feature learning without changing the basic training algorithm.

** Analysis and Limitations **

Shallow networks learn simple nonlinear relationships.
Deep networks approximate complex functions more effectively.
However, deeper models may face vanishing gradients and slower convergence.
Performance depends on activation choice and proper parameter initialization.
